 continue colonialist ambitions toward totalizing ways of seeing. But she also shows how artists stage dimensionality to articulate what remains invisible and irreducible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aComputational photography. 0aMass mediaxAesthetics. 0aTechnologyxAesthetics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393875?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393875423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393875/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles